First we need to download the required packages for what we want to do.

#install.packages("ggplot2")
#install.packages("tidyverse")
#install.packages("lubridate")
#install.packages("dbplyr")
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(dbplyr)

Now we load in the data and set the format for date and time.

data<- read_csv("/Users/ip367316/Downloads/IPWS_202310_202312.csv")
data$DateTime<-  mdy_hm(data$`Date & Time`, tz = "EST") #Tells R how to read the date and time data

Plotting Data

Now we can make a simple plot of the data.

ggplot(data) + geom_line(aes( x = `DateTime`, y = `Temp(F)`)) + #Assigns X and Y values for the plot
  scale_x_datetime(date_labels = ("%m/%d/%Y"), breaks = "1 weeks", guide = guide_axis(angle = 45))+ #Sets date format
  theme_linedraw()+ #Sets the background to a nice pre-set
  xlab("Date") + #Label for Y axis
  ylab("Temperature (F)") #Label for X axis

Below is an example of the same graph but plotting rainfall. Play around with the Y values and see what other variable look like. Make sure you adjuct the ylab accordingly!

ggplot(data) + geom_line(aes( x = `DateTime`, y = `Rain(in)`)) + #Assigns X and Y values for the plot
  scale_x_datetime(date_labels = ("%m/%d/%Y"), breaks = "1 weeks", guide = guide_axis(angle = 45))+ #Sets date format
  theme_linedraw()+ #Sets the background to a nice pre-set
  xlab("Date") + #Label for Y axis
  ylab("Precip (in)") #Label for X axis

Cleaning Data

Assuming these low temp values are outliers, we use the following code to remove them.

new_data<- data %>% filter(`Temp(F)` > 0)

Now we can remake the original plot but with the cleaner data.

ggplot(new_data) + geom_line(aes( x = `DateTime`, y = `Temp(F)`), ) + #Assigns X and Y values for the plot
  scale_x_datetime(date_labels = ("%m/%d/%Y"), breaks = "1 weeks", guide = guide_axis(angle = 45))+ #Sets date format
  theme_linedraw()+ #Sets the background to a nice pre-set
  xlab("Date") + #Label for Y axis
  ylab("Temperature (F)") #Label for X axis

Basic Stats

Lets get some basic stats for this filtered temperature data.

mean(new_data$`Temp(F)`) #Calulates the average of the dataset
## [1] 49.77645
sd(new_data$`Temp(F)`) #Calculates the standard deviation of the dataset
## [1] 10.51128
quantile(new_data$`Temp(F)`) #Gives you the quartiles of the dataset
##   0%  25%  50%  75% 100% 
##   27   42   49   57   84

We can also begin to explore the relationship between different variables. Lets see how temperature and solar radiation are related to each other.

ggplot(new_data) + geom_point(aes(x = `Solar_Rad(W/m^2)`, y = `Temp(F)`)) + 
  geom_smooth(aes(x = `Solar_Rad(W/m^2)`, y = `Temp(F)`), method = "lm") + #This adds a trendline 
  theme_linedraw()+ #Sets the background to a nice pre-set
  xlab(expression ("Solar Radiation"~W/m^2)) + #Label for Y axis
  ylab("Temperature (F)") #Label for X axis

R does not give you the equation and r2 value of the trendline by default. Lets calculate it using simple linear rgeression

trendline<- lm(new_data$`Temp(F)`~ new_data$`Solar_Rad(W/m^2)`)
summary(trendline)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = new_data$`Temp(F)` ~ new_data$`Solar_Rad(W/m^2)`)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
## -31.83  -7.38  -0.38   6.62  32.70 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                 4.838e+01  7.165e-02  675.27   <2e-16 ***
## new_data$`Solar_Rad(W/m^2)` 3.759e-02  8.095e-04   46.44   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 10.07 on 23966 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.08254,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.08251 
## F-statistic:  2156 on 1 and 23966 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Theres a lot of info up there so lets pick out whats important. Find the column that says Estimate. The first row is the y intercept, which in this case is 48.38 written in scientific notation. The value just below that is the slope of the equation, 0.00375. The r square value can be found on the second to last line and in this case we use the adjusted R2 which is 0.082. Finally, the significance of the relationshio between the two is given by the p-value of 2.2X10^-16

We may also want to simply test the correlation, r, between these two variables.

cor(new_data$`Temp(F)`,new_data$`Solar_Rad(W/m^2)`) #This will calculate and print the r value
## [1] 0.2873056

Bonus

One last fun graph you may be interested in making is a wind rose diagram. Here we have to turn to another package and do some data processing.

#install.packages("openair")
library(openair)
new_data_wr<- new_data %>% 
  filter(Wind_Direction != "NA") 
new_data_wr$WD<- case_when(new_data_wr$Wind_Direction == "N" ~ 360, 
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "NNE" ~ 22.5,
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "NE" ~ 45,
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "ENE" ~ 67.5,
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "E" ~ 90,
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "ESE" ~ 112.5,
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "SE" ~ 135, 
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "SSE" ~ 157.5, 
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "S" ~ 180,
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "SSW" ~ 202.5,
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "SW" ~ 225, 
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction == "WSW" ~ 247.5, 
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "W" ~ 270,
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "WNW" ~ 292.5, 
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "NW" ~ 315, 
                                new_data_wr$Wind_Direction  == "NNW" ~ 337.5 )
windRose(new_data_wr, ws = "Wind_Speed(mph)", wd = "WD", paddle = F)
